				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple laptop refresh
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1767357">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Nadiar</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1767355#post1767355" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">No one can trip over an Apple cord, because it will just pop off.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Brilliant! I can't believe that never occurred to me, then again I always run my cords well out of walking range.<br />
<br />
And yeah, I know all about the magnets. Every time someone brings back a failed drive at work and I get my hands on it, I pry it apart and steal the two in there so I can stick more humor to my cube.<br />
<br />
I'm still wary of resting large headphones or speakers near a hard drive.<br />
<br />
I also still wear a grounding strap every time I pop a PC open.<br />
<br />
*shrugs*<br />
<br />
Probably just paranoid, but I figure better safe than sorry. Especially because just today, one of our field techs went to replace a BBWC on an HP RAID controller, didn't ground, wasn't in a clean room, and managed to lose all of the config information on the controller, which necessitates a complete rebuild of the Exchange Server because apparently, as said tech noticed an hour before, the backups on site had not been occurring due to a lack of disk space on the SAN.  (oops! Someone's going to get their ass kicked for not properly configuring alerting at that site!)
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
