		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple laptop refresh
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1767956">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							So far the only real issues I've ran into while switching from my ASUS   to my Apple laptop was Truecrypt on OS X not being able to read my   Truecrypt volumes created on windows 7 because of the filesystem choices   I had made.  I googled around a bit regarding this and was not able to   find a solution to it, so that entailed moving data off of my external   drive that used full disk encryption to another drive then  reformatting  it so that it was usable on my mac.  I wish OS X natively  had stronger  encryption options, but it is sufficient and adequate,  albeit less  overkill and therefore less cool to me.  I'll be keeping my  eye on Time  Capsule iterations and possibly change to that or set up a  better system  myself for backup purposes.<br />
<br />
The other thing I ran into was I  should have been able to just copy  over the relevant emacs directories  and configuration and everything  would work.  Being emacs and there  being 100 ways to accomplish the  same task that was of course not the  case.  That was <i>extremely</i>  frustrating and I nearly said screw it  and just used VIM as it copied  over correctly and just worked without  issue.  For someone with a  greater grasp of the dark magics underlying  emacs configuration it  would have been quick to resolve I imagine, but  it was tedious and  something I intend to never have to go through again  now. I figured out  what was causing the snafu and things went fine there  after.  <br />
<br />
OS X has a really <i>weird</i> concept of how  fullscreen should work  when multiple displays are present that I expect  to be changed in the  future, as it is bizarre and idiotic.  Unlike  Wolfram's Mathematica,  Mathworks does not have a native implementation  of its CAS (Matlab) and  utilizes X11 as a shortcut instead of Cocoa.   Considering how  expensive Matlab is (especially once you start adding in  optional  toolkits) that is unacceptable.  Its Linux client is well done  as is  its Windows version, but they decided to just mail it in on the  OS X  version.  It works fine still and everything, I just find such  behavior  distasteful considering its ubiquity and expense.  Mathworks is  now on  my shitlist of companies until that situation is resolved.  In  the  mean time I will be actively hoping they go bankrupt or Mathematica   performs much better for numerical computing (unlikely).<br />
<br />
Parallels  is very well implemented thus far, so using Windows apps  alongside OS X  apps is a snap.  I do not find it wanting in comparison  to VMWare for  personal use, which is nice to encounter.  I haven't had  reason to use my Linux VM thus far thanks to homebrew (which is similar  to Debian's apt-get) and native OS X apps.  It is one less thing to  manage so that is a win for myself.<br />
<br />
I am likely going to build a desktop for gaming purposes though so that I  can max out all the graphics on games and such customization appeals to  me.<br />
<br />
As an aside, I think Apple really must simplify iTunes.  I  realize it does a tremendous amount of things in the same app, and I  realize that Apple wants people to be able to access the store easily  and simply, which is fine, but everything else related to content  management in the Apple ecosystem that relies on iTunes is incredibly  convoluted and contrary to all other Apple products in its usability.   I've been using the application for over a decade so it is not so bad  for myself as I incrementally gained familiarity with its quirks, but  for someone coming into using it blind it is daunting and many things  are unintuitive.  <br />
<br />
iTunes 11 made discoverability of features  even worse IMO.  It has a sleeker look to it and a better presentation  of some information, but everything else it made harder and  kafka'esque.  It's not even as though with that strife the user gains  features or potency in proportion to the frustration endured either.   Some things that should be trivial to accomplish are just arduous for no  reason from an end user's perspective.  It is actually so bad now that I  consider it a reason not to recommend their products to someone, if  that product relies on it by default.  <br />
<br />
And, it is really buggy  too on both platforms.  Importing media never caused issues in earlier  iterations, I've had it crash numerous times though in the latest  version in the process, which unacceptable for products attempting to  appeal to the pernickety consumer.  The actual iTunes store is well done  (although I think power searches should be more accessible from the  starting page myself), everything else in the iTunes program is just  ugh.  iTunes is a classic example of feature creep to the detriment of  its usefulness.  I don't have any suggestions on how to overcome the  present situation and can only provide the assessment that the current  situation sucks for the typical usage case.  It's a situation where if I  had more hands I would give the application four thumbs down.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="after_content">
				
