				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple laptop refresh
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1768457">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>MI Redeux</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1768454#post1768454" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Yeah, Apple uses their own file system inherited from Mac OS with some changes in OS X.  <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system#OS_X" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_system#OS_X</a>  <br />
<br />
I don't think it's used anywhere else in computing.  Seems bizarre that it is nontrivial to use various filesystems on the proprietary operating systems when it is so trivial in bsd/linux.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>I think its deliberate to contain the ecosystem.   Why windows cannot read EXT2,3,4 is silly as its an open file system.<br />
<br />
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BTRFS" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BTRFS</a><br />
<br />
Is likely to be the future primary FS for Linux,  it is still flagged as unstable but it contains many improves over the ext file systems.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
