		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple laptop refresh
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1769567">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							So, I have some more experience with the 13&quot; Macbook Air and OS X now. I had not really used it for years until getting one of their newer ones.  Also, I got an Apple TV (3rd generation).<br />
<br />
Initially I was really requiring that the laptop be &lt; 14&quot;, &lt; 4 lbs, and have at least a 1920x1080 resolution, and I really like as much res as possible, but I ended up getting the Apple anyways because it has a great battery life, and my friend got me a 20% discount on it (he works there) which made it much less money even with getting all maxed out settings.<br />
<br />
OS X has an incredible amount of integration with its other services, facebook, and twitter, and it has the best mouse gestures bar none.  Safari fully supports those gestures, but Firefox does not and Safari's plugins are sorely lacking so I use Firefox for most everything due to having a very good set up for it, unfortunately the Firefox devs chose not to have support for all the mouse gestures or even any of them despite those being prevalent on all the Apple computers, which is dumb but whatever.<br />
<br />
The laptop being much smaller and about 15 lbs less weight than my 17&quot; Asus that I had before has been great.  It is light as a feather in my backpack and takes up virtually no space, and because the laptop has a great battery life I don't have to work near a power plug all the time (the ASUS had like 1 hr battery life and its power management was uber buggy, a lot of times coming from sleep or using the ac adaptor after having it on battery power would rev all the processors to 100% and make everything slow as hell). <br />
 <br />
I was using VMWare and Linux on my PC before as I don't like to develop on Windows as much and Mathworks and Wolfram had Matlab and Mathematic clients for UNIX/Linux, so I could use the Linux environment and its sick toolchains while still having access to my other apps. I run Parallels on my Mac to run any Windows apps I need.  Parallels is like VMWare but performs slightly better on a mac than VMWare allegedly. <br />
<br />
One really killer feature that using a VM presents presently if you are a Java developer or a developer on something that relies on Java is that I can run Parallels or VMWare and make a VM that contains my same OS or another one (I use Linux in my VM, as it has sick synergy without the cons of running it as the Host OS, which is your one outside the VM) with Java on it and the IDE that you use and only have those things on it.  <br />
<br />
That way if the VM gets owned due to the Java insecurities that came out recently and are uber devestating it is not a big deal as you can just restore from an automatically generated snapshot and none of your sensitive stuff like emails and finance info and contacts or even just your computing resoruces are revealed).  Basically the attacker's efforts would have been in vain.  So, you can lol at viruses and malware that shows up like a boss.  <br />
<br />
Virtualbox is a free, open source Virtual Machine software that is decent, but Parallels and VMWare have some more features that are very nice and are not too expensive, so they are worth it, but if you are frugal Virtualbox is a good choice or use it as a way to trial if Virtual Machines are something you benefit from.  <br />
<br />
It's the way to do Java development currently though IMO.  It would be shitty to take down an entire network with root kits etc. due to someone inadvertently getting rooted out of no fault of their own other than having Java installed.  I got some people converted to this set up this week after listing all the benefits to it; even one professor went along with it, as well as using Intellij instead of Net Beans or Eclipse in the class.<br />
<br />
I don't use Crashplan anymore for backups.  I use the built in time machine and an external hard drive instead, which works fine along with my Google Drive.  OS X's great support of Linux/Unix apps through Homebrew is superb as well.  Homebrew is basically apt-get for OS X, so I can manage those apps super easily and install them as well that way.  It rules.  <br />
<br />
I love the facebook and twitter integration on OS X and notifications work perfectly IMO.  Whenever I get a post from twitter or facebook or a messages txt it shows up and I can view it there or click on it to access it.  The best thing in OS X is having messages on the desktop.  I can turn my phone off and still get most messages. <br />
 <br />
Another great feature is FaceTime built in, so if I get a FaceTime call sent to my phone I can do it on my macbook, which I love.  I do wish the camera on the macbook line was 1080p but I see why they don't use that to save bandwidth for other people.  They could have a 720p option when the conversations will happen over a cell network though, which would be a clever solution, I'm not sure if that is possible though without working with the cell company.<br />
<br />
iPhoto is great for uploading my pictures from my camera and sending and receiving pictures on Photostream, which is a service that runs in the background keeping things synced on your phone and macbook and as a backup service.  OS X has the contacts, calendar, mail, and photo apps natively like those on your phone so they interact great.  The e-mail program on OS X is very good as well. <br />
 <br />
I can manage all my e-mail accounts on there, either via imap or pop3.  It is a very slick interface and has great search features.  It can probably do much fancier things but that works for me.  Calendar supports Google calendar and such, but it is not such a big bonus with iCloud syncing calendars now.  Still it is nice and Google calendar has some extra features for working with groups that Calendar lacks iirc. <br />
 <br />
Oh, OS X has a reminders app too that will notify alarms whenever you go to certain spots or a certain time.  I am not a huge fan of it though as it is not nearly as obnoxious in pointing out that you need to get somewhere as the notification is uber quiet/small and it isn't as frequent as I would like. So, I don't use it on my phone that much or at all now.  Maybe when they get it more full featured though, it's pretty weaksauce atm.<br />
<br />
Where OS X really shines and Apple TV is how easy it is to make photo albums to send to other Apple users (they need to make it more accessible w/o having to make everything public though with other non-OS X/iOS people for it to be super great though). An area where it gains the advantage over the other media center devices is Airplay. <br />
 <br />
What Airplay does is allow you to (with just one click) mirror what is on the Apple TV to the iPad or iPhone and also let you put what is on your OS X screen onto the screen the Apple TV is connected to.  I use the last bit a lot if I am watching something locally. <br />
 <br />
I highly recommend buying Beamer (15 dollars online, it's not on the App Store) though as it supports pretty much every codec so you can stream MKV/AVI etc. encoded files onto the TV without having to hook the pc up to the tv over a wire.  Also doing it this way lets you control the device with your iPhone/iPad or the remote control that comes with the Apple TV.  I didn't really consider the Apple TV all that great compared to the Rokio devices, but when you use it with the Apple ecosystem it becomes really good.<br />
<br />
iTunes Match is really great on OS X too.  It's &lt; 30 bucks a year and puts all of your songs in the cloud that aren't on iTunes or gives you access to the songs on iTunes that match the songs you already have.  It was super trivial to get working, in fact I don't think I had to do anything other than pay for it.  Spotify has an OS X client that works just like the one on Windows, which is great.  VLC has a client too (it's the best media player in the world IMO and has many advanced features) for tweaking audio and video playback that happens to be out of sync and audio levels to fix poorly mixed videos.<br />
<br />
Apple makes Xcode, which is a development environment for iOS and such, and it is okay (I used to use it when I was on my Powerbook G4), but I much prefer the UNIX tool chains that I am familiar with and VIM or Emacs as they are really powerful, and Intellij makes IDEA for OS X, which is actually what they use internally at Apple instead of Xcode surprisingly. <br />
 <br />
To be fair, it is a really kick ass IDE though.  It's the best GUI app I've ever seen. It's super slick.  It is great for Python or Java, especially Java, as the options with VIM and Emacs are pretty bad compared to it, even though they are usually great.  Also, the IDE has a dark option, which looks very pretty and what I prefer.  <br />
<br />
Okay, the bad that I've encountered.  Setting up Emacs was a massive pain in the dick compared to Linux.  I thought it would just work (VIM did out of the box when I ported over my settings from Linux) but that so did not happen.  It took like 10 hours or so ironing out all the stuff that was causing errors on start up, which would have been avoided entirely for more experienced people that had a smarter set up, but just copying my directory and my .emacs file blew up in my face big time.  <br />
<br />
Another bad thing I guess is that out of the box Apple TV does not support a lot of codecs making getting Beamer pretty much a must for those of us who get our media at places other than iTunes.  Another thing that went badly was that my Truecrypt encrypted external drive did not have exactly the right configuration for what the Apple implementation of NTFS reader can read.  <br />
<br />
So, I had to hook my hard drive back up to my PC, then transfer the files over an easy transfer cable (<a href="http://www.amazon.com/Dynex-Data-transfer-Cable-Mac/dp/B005OAZHCM/ref=cm_rdp_product" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.amazon.com/Dynex-Data-tra...cm_rdp_product</a>) for the files that I did not want to lose after reformatting my external hard drive so I could use it on my macbook with Time Machine. <br />
 <br />
One more thing is that when I chose the configuration options for my Macbook Air and maxxed out the settings, getting the i7 instead of the i5, the battery life went from 7 hours to 5 hours, which I had not realized was going to happen.  So, I kind of wish I had went with the i5 in retrospect.  It's a reason I will upgrade next refresh most likely as 7 hours compared to 5 hours is a huge difference.  You can get most of a day's work out of that, and especially in airports that is great in the event of layover hell.<br />
<br />
Also, while the encryption options that OS X offers by default for users is good and the common options for MS and Apple, the nerd in me wishes they used Truecrypt by default and I could use the way overkill (for now) options like I had before and use keyfiles on a thumb drive that I have to have 2 factor security on my mac/pc. <br />
 <br />
I could download it and redo my set up again, but it would likely mess up how OS X manages power saving and log ins, making it more of a pain in the ass than necessary, although definitely much more cool, and along with polarized, dark sunglasses (that I wear at night naturally) and black, northface jacket aid in my delusions of being Adam Jenson in real life.<br />
<br />
Another thing is that while the battery life is great and the processor/hdd/ram are great on the Apple computer line, at least with the 13&quot; devices, playing any modern games on it is laughable.  I tried to load up The Witcher 2 and the game said &quot;lolnope&quot;, and it was entirely unplayable on even the low settings.  Oh well, just means I get more work done... would be nice though. <br />
<br />
Overall I would say that I definitely am glad that I got the macbook air (and that my friend hooked me up with the discount as a christmas gift).  I've seen the light on getting small and light laptops and leaving the heavy loading for the cloud/cluster/uber pc instead of trying to do an all in one machine that not only is upgradeable but also is only suitable for Hercules to carry around.  I agree with Linux Torvalds that any functional laptop should be &lt; 3 lbs. and have a high resolution on it (which current ones do not, except for some PC laptops I think).  <br />
<br />
I almost got the macbook retina, but I am glad that I did not after seeing how poor the integrated gpu that Intel makes perform. I plan on selling my Macbook Air next Retina refresh though assuming the reviews don't say how horrible the frame rate lag is and how the device needs more GPU for the 13&quot;.  The 15&quot; has a discrete GPU but I don't want a 15&quot; laptop.  I had one before and it is a size to where you don't want to use it in many places, and you can't tote it around in a small bag like a hipster. <br />
 <br />
The Apple TV especially though is a thing that you have to use to really appreciate because on the surface it looks a lot worse of an option than the other choices like the Roko (sp?) media center, but it has really tight integration with the entire ecosystem; you can tell that there was a lot of planning in foresight when it came to how everything was going to work together between the iOS and OS X line of things. <br />
 <br />
That sort of cohesion between the entire ecosystem is something that everyone should emulate.  MS is in a huge position to crush everyone similarly on this between the Surface tablets, the Windows phones, Windows, and the XBOX.  The consoles especially is an area where they could gg everyone due to its ubiquity.  It would definitely be a huge selling point, and MS could have client support on both Windows and OS X and Linux even, where as Apple really shines only on iOS/OS X devices. <br />
 <br />
Take messages for instance, it only works between OS X and iOS, so Windows and Android users are SOL, which I think is a big misstep.  Historically, they only had the iPod for mac users initially, but went with Windows and OS X on the 2nd gen ones and became the player that dwarfed all other music players. <br />
 <br />
Having messages on Windows and Android would be a big lure for people to get interested in even more Apple products after seeing how cool they are.  It's an area where Android currently sucks horribly and iOS could make up big ground there as messages is great on iOS/OS X, but unfriendly for Android users.  <br />
<br />
They would kill all other IM clients over night if they did and it's not as though IM is novel anymore. IM clients like Pidgin go for supporting all protocols instead of people just being on AIM or ICQ and saying screw all other things.  Messages should be similarly an open protocol and gg Aim, MSN, Skype, etc. <br />
 <br />
If they made FaceTime an open standard (which they should) it would be great as well as I love FaceTime, but doing so with other users outside of OS X/iOS isn't something that happens, so that means resorting to Google Hang outs or Skype, with Google Hang outs being the best option presently.<br />
<br />
Another cool feature of OS X, well a few cool features, is launcher, expose,  and mission control, and virtual desktops making program and workflow management very fast and efficient.  They should consolidate that space some more instead of having 3 different keyboard buttons for it, which is somewhat confusing for an end user.  <br />
<br />
Virtual desktops are great (and a sweet feature on Linux for instance) for organizing the different related programs opened or windows contained in those programs so that you are only tabbing through or seeing programs related to the task at hand or grouped by workflow.  Like I can have my entertainment stuff on one desktop, then my work stuff on another, and IRC/IM on the entertainment stuff which ultimately means less distractions and it is more zen as a result.<br />
<br />
Which reminds me, OS X bizarrely has two weird features that are basically retarded and make no sense to do this way.  It has super poor efficiency on managing a program windows dimensions, even something basic like Windows 7's window key+left/up/down/right does not exist, leaving you to press a weird combo even to just move the screen dimensions to the left or right or you have to do everything by hand by clicking and holding onto the window corners.  <br />
<br />
That is not so bad when you have an external mouse, but when you are using the touch pad you can't use a gesture anymore and you have to depress the key.  That is very uncomfortable for my fingers and as someone who has bad RSI that has to take care to not over do it so that my career doesn't end early I try to avoid that entirely. My hands are increasingly becoming less effected by RSI though, healing some over time I guess due to having much better practices and taking better care of my hands.  <br />
<br />
I was very concerned for a while though, thinking I had screwed myself really badly and would have to change careers entirely to something that wasn't so reliant on finger usage unlike working in tech where everything is done on a computer, from designs to coding to communication etc. That would have been extremely debilitating and I don't even know what I would have done if I had not been able to recover some.<br />
<br />
Thankfully (FSM be praised) by using some Aspercreme (I had no faith that this would help any but it actually did, very effectively somehow; it seemed like snake oil going into it) a much more ergonomic keyboard and mouse, and following doctor recommendations with break frequency my hands aren't raging pissed at me all the time.  It also meant I could not play video games at all without being punished for doing so.  And I love video games.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
