		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow has_after_content">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple laptop refresh
				</h2>
				

						
						
							
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1769583">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							To be fair, iTunes is a piece of shit on OS X too.  It is super buggy and will crash if you add files to it that aren't the file types it is searching for, like if it encounters a txt file in a folder that has songs/movies in it iTunes will crash every time.  The new iTunes 11 UI completely moved tons of stuff around and finding out where the iPhone/iPod interface is is non-trivial.  I absolutely hate iTunes.  It used to be good on mac, like a decade ago.  It has continually gotten worse.  <br />
<br />
They need to bust the software up so that it is a complete failure instead of having this one gargantuan program that handles all of this: books, movies, songs, podcasts, purchasing apps, books, songs, movies, and magazines, and also maintaining and organizing the library data base for all of the above, and what makes it a super pita on top of that is that it purposefully does not support a wide range of media encodings, so you have to either reencode and lose quality or go through an app like beamer for instance to overcome that.  Changing iTunes libraries like when I got a new computer was something that you just don't do. It's completely stupid in that way, well multiple ways.<br />
<br />
To make iTunes suck less they need to turn everything into a modular design:<br />
1) put strictly the media management and importing into one app<br />
2) put the apple store on their website instead of the app<br />
3) possibly put the books and magazines into a different UI<br />
4) support more codecs, they should at least be as competent as VLC's support<br />
5) make the media playback less terrible and ignore the wants of corps that want to stop people from being able to utilize AirPlay on certain devices. <br />
6) make iTunes less of a buggy disaster, being able to handle exceptions like running into just another filetype than what the import is looking for is absurd and busch league.<br />
<br />
There are probably more cases that I've encountered where iTunes is being dumb, but those are the ones that come to mind right now.  <br />
<br />
In my report of my experience with my new macbook I forgot to mention that the keyboard seems poorly constructed.  After just a month's time of moderate usage I've pretty much destroyed the 'j' key on it (j is used for movement in VIM, also concatenating adjacent actual lines (visual lines are not by default), and I have it set up to split (insert a new line at point) with a customization I made, so my j key gets quite a bit of usage.  <br />
<br />
I have a habit of using the j key to scroll line by line instead of moving a page at a time a lot, so it is depressed quite a bit.  Everytime I push it there's a snapping sound (usually), and due to how the laptop is designed it isn't something that is fixable.  I imagine that it is smooshed on there with all the other parts, so if I took it to a shop they would have to replace it entirely possibly just for a keyboard snafu.  I usually associate Apple with quality construction, but in this case they dropped the ball, at least on my unit.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
